    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-04-16T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-04-16T03:00:00-05:00" n="325"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d325">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1163/171: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-04-16T16:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 16, 1927—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 16—6:37 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Certain missionaries of the Methodist Episcopal Church, South, including Dr.
                    Nance, president of Soochow University, are contemplating returning to Soochow
                    in open defiance of advice and objections of this consulate general. I urge the
                    strongest negative representations to the home offices of these missionaries at
                    Nashville, Tennessee, to require their missionaries to heed consular advice in
                    the present emergency in China.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
